sub: Are USPM and EUPM good stylistic descriptors for power metal?
com:
I'm posting again because I didn't get any responses

USPM is generally defined as aggressive and riff-based, with bands including Manowar and Iced Earth, and EUPM is generally the more recognized approach with a lighter sound and keyboards.

If I have to be completely honest, I am not entirely sure if they are good differentiators when it comes to "style," because a good amount of the early German power that was associated with EUPM was just as aggressive, with bands like Blind Guardian and Running Wild. It doesn't exactly help that this riff style, especially US bands, has faded out since the early 90s, where bands with the softer approach are gaining more recognition in both continents., so it kind of made USPM as a scene obsolete nowadays (it doesn't mean that there aren't popular bands of this style anymore, as seen with Blind Guardian and Iced Earth). And finally, this style of riff-based power metal isn't really considered "pure" power metal by many, but more like a blend with traditional heavy metal or speed metal. New bands like Visigoth are often referred to as "new wave of traditional heavy metal." In extreme cases, some purists may even disregard those bands as anything "power metal," though I cannot exactly comment on that.

Now, I understand if we are talking about the scenes themselves, like how Floridan and Swedish death metal are treated more as distinct scenes rather than legitimately different death metal subgenres, or how Louisiana doom metal is not treated as differently as Maryland doom metal. However, in this case, we should consider Japanese power metal as its own scene as much as we do with US and European, which does seem to be the case.
